  "prompt": "What are the laws to change your status from a student visa to a green card in the US, how do they compare to the immigration laws in Canada?",
  "response": "I'll break this down for the US and Canada:\n\nUnited States (Student Visa to Green Card):\n1. Common pathways:\n- Employment-based green card\n- Marriage to a US citizen\n- Extraordinary ability visa\n- H-1B work visa transition\n- Optional Practical Training (OPT) route\n\nKey requirements:\n- Maintain legal student status\n- No significant gaps in legal presence\n- Sponsorship from employer or spouse\n- Meet specific employment/relationship criteria\n\nCanada (Student Visa to Permanent Residency):\n1. Primary routes:\n- Express Entry system\n- Provincial Nominee Programs\n- Canadian Experience Class\n- Post-graduation work permit\n- Job offer in specific skilled occupations\n\nKey differences from US:\n- More structured immigration points system\n- Faster processing times\n- More transparent permanent residency pathways\n- Less complex application procedures\n- Greater emphasis on skilled labor needs\n\nBoth countries:\n- Require consistent legal status\n- Background/security checks\n- Financial stability proof\n- Language proficiency\n- Educational/professional qualifications evaluation\n\nSpecific details can change, so consulting current immigration lawyers or official government websites is recommended for most up-to-date information.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of these immigration processes?",
